#!/bin/bash
# vpnctl postrm — spec §2.2's remove-vs-purge split, standard Debian
# convention: `apt remove` (arg "remove") keeps user profiles, `apt purge`
# (arg "purge") removes everything vpnctl ever created, including
# dependencies it installed itself (never ones that were already present —
# see postinst's installed_by_vpnctl.json).
#
# By the time this runs, prerm has already called `vpnctl down` for every
# user with an active profile, which tears down the namespace/iptables and
# restores sysctl from its own backup — so there is nothing network-related
# left to clean up here, only files.
set -u

STATE_DIR="/var/lib/vpnctl"
DEPS_FILE="$STATE_DIR/installed_by_vpnctl.json"

remove_state_dirs() {
  [ -d /root/.local/state/vpnctl ] && rm -rf /root/.local/state/vpnctl
  for d in /home/*/.local/state/vpnctl; do
    [ -d "$d" ] && rm -rf "$d"
  done
}

remove_config_dirs() {
  [ -d /root/.config/vpnctl ] && rm -rf /root/.config/vpnctl
  for d in /home/*/.config/vpnctl; do
    [ -d "$d" ] && rm -rf "$d"
  done
}

remove_installed_deps() {
  [ -f "$DEPS_FILE" ] || return 0
  installed_singbox="false"
  installed_awg="false"
  if command -v jq >/dev/null 2>&1; then
    installed_singbox="$(jq -r '.sing_box // false' "$DEPS_FILE" 2>/dev/null || echo false)"
    installed_awg="$(jq -r '.amneziawg // false' "$DEPS_FILE" 2>/dev/null || echo false)"
  else
    grep -q '"sing_box": *true' "$DEPS_FILE" && installed_singbox="true"
    grep -q '"amneziawg": *true' "$DEPS_FILE" && installed_awg="true"
  fi

  if [ "$installed_singbox" = "true" ]; then
    echo "vpnctl postrm: removing sing-box (installed by vpnctl)"
    rm -f /usr/local/bin/sing-box
  fi
  if [ "$installed_awg" = "true" ]; then
    echo "vpnctl postrm: removing amneziawg-tools/amneziawg-go (installed by vpnctl)"
    rm -f /usr/local/bin/awg-quick /usr/local/bin/awg /usr/local/bin/amneziawg-go
  fi
}

case "${1:-}" in
  remove)
    # Ephemeral runtime state is always cleared; user profiles are not
    # touched — that's the whole point of `remove` vs `purge`.
    remove_state_dirs
    ;;
  purge)
    remove_state_dirs
    remove_config_dirs
    remove_installed_deps
    rm -rf "$STATE_DIR"
    ;;
  *)
    # upgrade/failed-upgrade/etc: nothing to do
    ;;
esac

exit 0
